erDAV_XH1hq7Ew8uM0M3T6uWN4-RTL0DywFikhb32-RZyGDguxpl8SB-z_Eb86pYzCfAf7w4NYtwl4OWz0q77aW6mqG3HoxObr9baXN7qeXObF4eswnbs_hOGxEpeUY4xgAgHiI0GMQ==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class usage in coverage**\\n\\nI need to figure out how to utilize a public or natural path for class$ in closure2, but it seems it’s only present as unused. It might be generated for static class literals, though javap shows no usage in the code. The dynamic report lists class$ for every Groovy class, suggesting it's generated but not typically called.\\n\\nI’m pondering why this coverage isn't showing, especially with MethodHandle. It might be that coverage tools track source call sites by bytecode. There could be a need to use Java reflection to execute class$ since that's recognized by coverage tools.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering coverage solutions**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether to add Method.invoke to help with coverage. The call site still shows class$, and maybe coverage isn't including it because MethodHandle invoke is intrinsic. It’s puzzling since bytecode still references Class.forName.\\n\\nI want to add a Java Method dispatch test like closure3, but there's a conflict with the guideline against direct reflection unless absolutely necessary. The existing tests already use reflection. We might have to rely on MethodHandles again, but they failed before.\\n\\nI could add Method.invoke; however, I want to avoid direct reflection like getDeclaredMethod. It’s tricky since the public API doesn’t touch those unused compiler helpers. The previous closure3 test didn’t cover either, even though attempts were made. It looks like direct MethodHandles might be disabled, too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring coverage options**\\n\\nI’m considering that the active report might be generated after our current tests, which could explain the lack of coverage. It shows two attempts, likely from those tests. I wonder if I could directly call Class.forName from the test, but that wouldn’t work since the frame is for the test and not class$.\\n\\nWhat about using Groovy’s MOP to invoke the static method? The class$ is package-private static, and dynamic Groovy seems able to access it. I might need to add a test in Java with GroovyShell, though dynamic class loading isn't ideal. How can I retrieve the stack effectively?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_fWn1WlAJY6P8ysCbcH57CpWO|fc_084be9eae175307e016a00a17b5670819fb500964bead6935d", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/MapCreatorInner_createArgumentArray_closure2Test.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.lang.invoke.MethodType;\nimport java.util.Map;\n\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertSame;\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertThrows;\n", "newText": "import java.lang.invoke.MethodType;\nimport java.lang.reflect.InvocationTargetException;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Method;\nimport java.util.Map;\n\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertInstanceOf;\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertSame;\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertThrows;\n"}, {"oldText": "    @Test\n    void compilerGeneratedClassResolverReportsMissingClass() throws Throwable {\n        MethodHandle classResolver = classResolver();\n\n        assertThrows(\n                NoClassDefFoundError.class,\n                () -> classResolver.invokeWithArguments(\"io.restassured.internal.DoesNotExist\"));\n    }\n\n    @FunctionalInterface\n", "newText": "    @Test\n    void compilerGeneratedClassResolverReportsMissingClass() throws Throwable {\n        MethodHandle classResolver = classResolver();\n\n        assertThrows(\n                NoClassDefFoundError.class,\n        